name: ethyl indole-3-acrylate

Esters typically have a moderate influence on melting point due to their ability to engage in dipole-dipole interactions, albeit weaker than carboxylic acids. In ethyl indole-3-acrylate, the ester formed from acrylic acid and ethanol is expected to raise the melting point moderately. The double bond itself does not substantially raise the melting point, but it adds rigidity to the molecule which can contribute slightly. The ethoxy group is relatively small and will have only a minor effect on the melting point. Taking into account the individual effects, we predict the melting point will be as follows: - Indole base structure: +50 (due to rigidity and molecular interactions) - Ester group derived from acrylic acid: +20 (due to dipole-dipole interactions and increased molecular weight) - Ethoxy group: +5 (minor contribution due to its small size) - Alkenyl double bond: +10 (due to added rigidity) - Overall addition from these groups: +85
